---
// src/pages/saudi-mandi-slow-pit-cooked-traditional-guide-2026.astro
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Saudi Mandi Guide: Slow Pit-Cooked Feast 2026" 
  description="Master the art of Saudi Mandi. Discover how this smoky, tender meat and rice dish is cooked in underground pit ovens, and its culinary history."
  canonicalUrl="https://www.sauditravelhub.com/saudi-mandi-slow-pit-cooked-traditional-guide-2026/"
>
  <script slot="head" type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [{
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is Mandi traditionally cooked?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Mandi is traditionally slow-cooked underground in a clay oven (tandoor). The meat is suspended above the rice, allowing its seasoned drippings to flavor the rice below while cooking."
      }
    }, {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between Kabsa and Mandi?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "While both use rice and meat, Kabsa is cooked in a single pot on a stove with a heavier tomato and spice base. Mandi is cooked underground, relies on charcoal smoke for flavor, and uses fewer direct spices in the rice."
      }
    }]
  }
  </script>

  <main id="main-content" style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 7rem 1.5rem 3rem; font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--white);">
    <!-- HERO SECTION -->
    <header style="margin-bottom: 3rem; text-align: center;">
      <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.15em; color: var(--gold); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Cuisine &amp; Dining · Slow Pit-Cooked Feast</div>
      <h1 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 2.75rem; line-height: 1.2; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; color: #fff;">Saudi Mandi: Slow Pit-Cooked Culinary Guide</h1>
      
      <div style="position: relative; border-radius: 12px; overflow: hidden; margin-top: 2rem; box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.3); border: 1px solid var(--border);">
        <img 
          src="/images/saudi_mandi_platter.png" 
          alt="Saudi Mandi slow-cooked meat and rice traditional dish" 
          loading="lazy"
          style="width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; max-height: 450px; object-fit: cover;" 
        />
        <div style="position: absolute; bottom: 0; left: 0; right: 0; background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(5,13,26,0.95) 0%, rgba(5,13,26,0.5) 60%, transparent 100%); padding: 1.5rem 2rem; text-align: left;">
          <p style="color: var(--white); font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0; font-style: italic; font-weight: 500; text-shadow: 1px 1px 3px rgba(0,0,0,0.95);">Meat and rice slow-cooked underground in a tandoor pit. Smoky, tender, unforgettable.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- TABS NAVIGATION -->
    <div class="tabs-nav" style="display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border); margin-bottom: 2rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <button class="tab-btn active" data-tab="guide" style="background: none; border: none; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--gold); padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; color: #fff; font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s ease;">Cooking Guide</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="background" style="background: none; border: none; border-bottom: 2px solid transparent; padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; color: var(--white-dim); font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s ease;">Background &amp; Origin</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="recent" style="background: none; border: none; border-bottom: 2px solid transparent; padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; color: var(--white-dim); font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s ease;">Recent Blogs</button>
    </div>

    <!-- TABS CONTENT -->
    <div class="tab-content" id="tab-guide" style="display: block;">
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 2rem; color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700;">The Underground Cooking Process</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Unlike stove-top rice dishes, authentic Mandi cannot be cooked in a standard home kitchen because it relies on a **tandoor** (an underground clay pit oven). Here is how master chefs prepare this legendary smoky feast in Saudi Arabia:</p>
      
      <div style="background: var(--surface2); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        <h4 style="color: var(--gold); font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Traditional Cooking Stats</h4>
        <ul style="list-style-type: none; padding-left: 0; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; font-size: 1rem;">
          <li>⏰ <strong>Cooking Time:</strong> 3 to 4 hours</li>
          <li>🔥 <strong>Oven Temp:</strong> ~250°C underground</li>
          <li>🍽️ <strong>Best For:</strong> Communal Feasts &amp; weddings</li>
          <li>🍖 <strong>Meat Options:</strong> Young camel, lamb, or chicken</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600;">How Mandi is Assembled</h3>
      <ol style="padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.75rem;">
        <li>1. <strong>Preheating the Pit:</strong> A fire is lit inside the deep clay pit oven using dry wood (like acacia or sidr). The wood burns down to hot, glowing coals.</li>
        <li>2. <strong>Seasoning the Rice:</strong> Large pots of seasoned basmati rice (with water, light cardamom, cloves, and bay leaves) are placed directly at the bottom of the pit, sitting just above the hot coals.</li>
        <li>3. <strong>Suspending the Meat:</strong> Whole spiced lambs, chickens, or young camel quarters are placed on metal racks suspended directly above the rice pots. No oil is added to the meat; it is simply rubbed with salt, turmeric, and saffron.</li>
        <li>4. <strong>Sealing the Pit:</strong> The oven pit is covered with a heavy metal lid and sealed airtight using wet clay or heavy blankets. This traps all steam, smoke, and heat inside.</li>
        <li>5. <strong>The Dripping Effect:</strong> As the meat slow-cooks, its fat and seasoned juices drip directly down onto the bubbling rice below, infusing it with incredible flavor.</li>
        <li>6. <strong>Smoking:</strong> Before opening, hot charcoal is sometimes doused with oil in a small cup inside to give the entire dish a deep, woody smoke flavor.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="tab-background" style="display: none;">
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 2rem; color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700;">Origins &amp; Cultural Significance</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Mandi originated in the Hadhramaut region of Yemen, but it has become a deeply rooted national favorite across Saudi Arabia. It is considered the ultimate communal feast, served at weddings, Eid celebrations, and large family gatherings.</p>
      
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;"><strong>The Science of the Pit:</strong> Pit cooking is a ancient survival technique developed in dry desert environments where water and firewood were scarce. By cooking underground and sealing the pit, the moisture from the meat and rice is trapped, creating a high-pressure steam cooker. This allowed Bedouins to tenderize tough cuts of desert meats like mature camel and goat without letting moisture escape.</p>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 2rem;"><strong>Etiquette:</strong> Like Kabsa, Mandi is served on a massive shared metal platter. The smoky rice forms the base, topped with falling-off-the-bone meat. Out of respect, guests are served the prime cuts (like the shoulder or leg). A side of raw onions, green chilies, and a cold tomato salsa (dakous) is always served to balance the rich, smoky flavors.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="tab-recent" style="display: none;">
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 2rem; color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700;">Explore More Saudi Food Guides</h2>
      <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem;">
        <a href="/saudi-arabia-traditional-food-guide-15-dishes/" style="display: block; padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; background: var(--surface2); color: #fff; text-decoration: none; transition: border-color 0.3s ease;">
          <strong style="color: var(--gold); display: block; font-size: 1.1rem;">📖 15 Traditional Saudi Dishes &rarr;</strong>
          <span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--white-dim);">Compare all the major rice, meat, street food, and dessert options in the Kingdom.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/saudi-kabsa-recipe-traditional-guide-2026/" style="display: block; padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; background: var(--surface2); color: #fff; text-decoration: none; transition: border-color 0.3s ease;">
          <strong style="color: var(--gold); display: block; font-size: 1.1rem;">🍗 Traditional Saudi Kabsa Recipe &rarr;</strong>
          <span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--white-dim);">Learn to make the famous national chicken and saffron rice dish.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/saudi-jareesh-hail-region-ancient-recipe-2026/" style="display: block; padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; background: var(--surface2); color: #fff; text-decoration: none; transition: border-color 0.3s ease;">
          <strong style="color: var(--gold); display: block; font-size: 1.1rem;">🌾 Hail Region Ancient Jareesh Recipe &rarr;</strong>
          <span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--white-dim);">Discover the heritage of Saudi Arabia's oldest crushed wheat comfort dish.</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <script slot="body">
    const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn');
    const contents = document.querySelectorAll('.tab-content');
    buttons.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        buttons.forEach(b => {
          b.classList.remove('active');
          b.style.borderBottomColor = 'transparent';
          b.style.color = 'var(--white-dim)';
        });
        contents.forEach(c => c.style.display = 'none');
        btn.classList.add('active');
        btn.style.borderBottomColor = 'var(--gold)';
        btn.style.color = '#fff';
        const target = document.getElementById(`tab-${btn.dataset.tab}`);
        target.style.display = 'block';
      });
    });
  </script>
</Layout>

<style>
  .tab-btn.active {
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--gold) !important;
    color: #fff !important;
  }
</style>
